---
import TopicLayout from '../../layouts/TopicLayout.astro';

const title = 'The Hertzsprung-Russell diagram';
const summary = 'The HR diagram is one of astronomy\u2019s most powerful maps, revealing how stars are grouped by temperature, brightness, and stage of life.';
const nextTopics = [
	{ slug: 'main-sequence', title: 'The main sequence' },
	{ slug: 'red-dwarfs-quiet-majority', title: 'Red dwarfs: the Galaxy\'s quiet majority' },
	{ slug: 'white-dwarfs-dead-stars-still-glowing', title: 'White dwarfs: dead stars still glowing' }
];
---

<TopicLayout
	title={title}
	summary={summary}
	topicNumber={13}
	nextTopics={nextTopics}
	viewer={{ variant: 'neighbourhood', topic: 'hr-diagram', showHr: true }}
>
	<p>
		The Hertzsprung-Russell (HR) diagram is not a map of space, but a map of physics.
		It plots a star's surface temperature (on the horizontal axis) against its
		luminosity or absolute magnitude (on the vertical axis).
	</p>
	<p>
		When stars are plotted this way, they do not fill the diagram randomly. Instead,
		they form distinct groups. The most prominent is the main sequence, a long
		diagonal strip where most stars (including the Sun) spend their lives.
	</p>
	<p>
		The HR diagram allows astronomers to quickly see how different types of stars
		are related and how they evolve over time. It is essentially a census of the
		stellar population, showing us the relative numbers of main-sequence stars,
		red giants, and white dwarfs.
	</p>

	<div class="callout panel">
		<p class="panel__eyebrow">A Powerful Tool</p>
		<h3>Visualising Stellar Evolution</h3>
		<p>
			The Gaia mission has produced the most detailed HR diagrams ever created,
			showing the "fine structure" of the stellar population and even allowing
			us to measure the age of different star clusters.
		</p>
	</div>

	<Fragment slot="viewer-guide">
		<h3>Live HR diagram</h3>
		<p>
			On the left is a 3D view of the stars around the Sun. On the right is a live
			Hertzsprung-Russell diagram built from the same stars. Each dot is coloured by
			its blackbody temperature — hot blue-white stars sit on the left, cool red stars
			on the right. Bright stars are at the top, faint stars at the bottom.
		</p>
		<p>
			The diagonal band running from upper-left to lower-right is the main sequence —
			where stars spend most of their lives fusing hydrogen. Below it you can see the
			white dwarf branch: hot but faint remnants of dead stars. As you fly through
			space with WASD, the loaded stars change and the diagram updates in real time.
			Try flying toward the Hyades cluster (roughly RA 4h 27m, Dec +16) and watch the
			diagram tighten into a narrow isochrone.
		</p>
	</Fragment>
</TopicLayout>
